s be\ning shipped out to the smelters.\nljewis A. Parkhurst, the well\nknown mining mail of this eity return\nrecently after a week\u2019s visit to the\ncanrp, anys tin Tonopah Sun. Mr. Park\nhurst expresst d himself as being very\nfavorably1 impressed with the outlook\nfor the cfcmp and is going back there\nin a few days\n\u2018\u20181 bud heard reports f the camp,\"\nsaid Mr. Parkhurst, \"but man w ants\nto see a emnttrr\u2014trk'\u2019tbnt-for-h*ti*s\u00ab4#j\nso 1 went out the,u: last Sunday ugd\nstayed until Saturday. I did hot an\nnoiinee myself oY astf anyone tir srhow\nme around. and most 01 my tune was\nspent in tile hills. T did not attempt\nto go down into any of the holes, for\nthe ore was on the dumps -Ail'd I\u2019 could\nsee for myself, also the formation of\nthe conn try. When I go there again\n1 am going to see what is at the bot\ntom of the shafts.\n\u2022i-\u2018I was favorably impressed with\nmsliiil 1 sam' it nil 1 tiiiivk btawhisle trie'\na very good1 chance. It looks to me as\u2019\nif there was going to be a lot of\nmoney made over there. Money is\ngetting in without a doubt for there\nis a great deal of money circulating.\nThe lemteTB are doing a great deal\ntoward* the. development of the\nand they are all getting good returns.\n1 saw -a big freight team going out\non Saturday and that was a very good\nsign. I see no reason why Rawhidi\nshould not make a good. camp. The\nroad (front, Alin* is iu good condition\nfor travel,1\u2019\nMrs. S. H.:Gillette, whose husband,\nhas secured a number of good things\nat Rawhiile. rutunied from a trip there\non Sunday. Mrs. Gillette thinks that\nthere has never been such a rush as\nthere is to te now camp.\n*\u2018I was there when the crowd from\nRenio xtutMiL.Kawhi.de. said she, aad\nthey were' all very much enthused\nover the npfienrnnce or the camp. A\nnumber of them spoke of returning,\nandi all were inquiring for the stock\nof hey .had visited Pep\npie Frjiii alt styles ut)d\nwe iUby^tegiu* ei$l\ner (oing in with freight or coming\nout 1 do not know from where th\nkJ 11 jitsVe iiim\u2018 WqjilJ\nwish ijo see. It in hard t( get ^hrotfg^\niBttiy sp.o .it :t..v time, ;tnd th\n/i^Rswmh -to b*1 working tit Rawhidi\ni'V'Sldfl .was there they hail been or\nI Iw* d a.comwiny to bring-hr tin fifei\nI rl gl\u00bb\u2019*jdhnf, and there was sonu\nU-nj w^iing arrangements fo\nlaiitTa t f f r< 1\niR t id man expci-tenb nii'fi1* ftfini\n!>o is planning to run a rtbr\ni v aw hi do, from Schur:',. Then r\nwo\u2019 obiles eom'ng and going till t'\nmil everybody is most enthus'\nflr over the outlook.\u201d\n-o\nl1 i tv (\u2019oininissioin r W C. Rud\ntur^ ^us ^onie in bo vy lock.\n-i\nCONTEST RIGHT t\nTO WATER SUP\nPLY at Imlay\nr* f 'i *r\nj f 1\nf t\nA big lawsuit and possibly an in\n\u2022junction is pending over the water\nrights at Imlay, the ijew division poipt\nwhich the railroad company is making\nto take the place, of VViune.niucca.\nChief Detectice Thacker of the Wells j\nFargo r-xpres\u00bb company claims the w.a j\nter right by which the. water supply is\nsecured for Imlay and threatens a suit\nunless he is paid his price for it by\nthe railroad company. On ll\u00bbe other\nhand the railroad company claims that\nit has a prior right to the water- -The\nwater is now being piped to Imlay and\nflows at the rate .about- 250,1)0 gal\nlons per day.\nWork a .t Imlay is still progressing\nbut not very rapidly- Only about six\nty men are now employed there. A\ntwelve stall roundhouse is being buill\nand lodging and boarding houses are\nbeing erected. It is thought that the\nforce will be increased in a. short\ntime.\n---o---\n.J. B. Case and daughter, Miss Fran\nces, are in town, called hen- by the\nsickness of J. 8. Case.\nWASHINGTON, March, L\u2014Ajneri\ncan railway have mad*? arringejinemts\nto comply with the provisions of. the\n\u201cnine-hour lay.* The operation\nthe law I will; mtMw the employment of\nseveral thousand additional operators\nand the dosing, of a large number of\nsmall station* 'on the. principal systems.\nWhile discontinuing of railway service\nat many points, it is though will induce\ntemporary inconvenience to the trav\neling an\u00bb(l. shipping public, in order\nto reduce1 dirafoAft 4>fvertiti\u00bblfc Expenses:\nwhich now seems necessary, the operat\ning officials of the railways believe that\nthey possibly can meet the situation\nwith which they are confronted.\nDuring the hearing of applications\nfor an extension of the. nine-hour law\nbv the Interstate Commerce Cominfs\nam, mw a*r<mM!iTnr StaTementt* were\nmade by the uperatiug officials of the\nimportant railways. A good many lines\nowing to a reduction In the revenues\ntpid jo their inability to' command the\ncash necessary to mispt their payrolls,\nhave been forced during tlu* past four\nI months almost to the point, of asking\nfor a receiver Tn the opinion of rail\nway officials, expressed tpt. the hearing\n\u2022tin b r oath and in private eAnwrsatioin\nthis condition dons nut seem to have\nbeen 'lue to the enforcement of reg\nulative laws or to the incapacity of\nrailway management. Most of the\nrailway officials attribute the difficulty\nto the unfortunate banking situation\nwb\u00ab:b dfeviuppad.,. UlP.\nrailways (lid not feel the stringency\nin money until about the first of No\nvember. In \u00a3act, the month of October\nwhs one-, jif the best in the history\nrtf the bufcibe* .\u25a0At Affierieiin failroad\niug..\n\u201cThen, without trie slightest warn\njug,\u201d li. Mixlge, vi<je-p\u00abapid#nt and\ngonorfct, rmrf afp>r\\ of the rK(tch Island\nayatem jesiureatei). .it,..\u2018.\u2018.ya ^fre pi\u00abng;.\ned from prosperity to adversity. A year\nago out system could not handle the\ntraffic offered us. Today wo have 10,\n00 idle ears. Five months ago we suf\nfered from a .congestipp of freight,\nnow we s'lilTAr' from a congestion of\nempty cars.\nWhat is true of the Rock Island is\ntrue of scores of other railroads.\n|6ne rnilwfcy official1 ventured the iptatp\niK>nt Chtiti in -.tlid anunav to 4av tb^r*I\nYere .^leffrt'i||J|(jf <ars\u00a3 flM $ij| 1\nline which he instanced was declared\nto be hauling empty ears backward\nuiitrururd -bycaum' it had not yard\nn<*\"4 r>ifiWtoM\u00abi\u2014i\u2014 iiimii\n,df| a9 single \u2022nffiffwl of a single rail\nway line vyho appeared before the Com\nesiofi, however* expressed the belief\nt the present industrial depression\nfWffld''dfii the testimony of\nearly everv witness before the Com\nMission, there was a note of confi-\nfV I \"tarise 'ugh fit* vgery one of\n\u2019frrh practically hVrievrd that the strin\nency in the money market ,rom which\nh\u2022(s -offered is not due to j\nmiamentnl causes. Thev point out\nt the crops last vear were good\n't prices were excellent; that indus-\nial enterjirises throughout the eoun-1\nwere flourishing. It was merely\nifoi ina^iUilvIi* oonwnhoil, readv j ehph\n'mi the hoarding of*' money \u20184>v ptniib'i\nIt Is Supposed Deceased Was ,a Former Resident\nof Rawhide, But Nothing Was Found to\nDisclose Identity Other Than\nthe Name of Adams\nHAD CERTIFICATE OF\nDEPOSIT IN FAIRVIEW BANK\ni ft\nWhether suicide, foul pldv. or nat\njral causes caused the death of L. W.\n(Adams, evidently a mining man, who\nwas found in a room in the Bell build\ning yesterday, all form themes for\nspeculation. That the latter is the\npause there is little doubt, although\nthe coroner has not as yet held an\nautopsy.\nFrom indications Adams had evi\ndently been dead since Sunday night\nor Monday, as decomposition had set\nin when the body was found. Adams\nis a stranger here, and registered at\nthe Bell house Tuesday night. He re\ntired early, and when the chamber\nmaid went to clean up the room Mon\nday, she saw the prostrate form' of\nthe man lying across the bed fully at\ntired. Thinking perhaps the man was\nsleeping off a drunk, she closed the\ndoor and thought nothing more of the\nmatter. Tuesday another, woman, an\nIndian squaw, saw the body of the mam\nbut Bhe, too, supposed he was in a\ndrunken stupor and, knowing, noth\ning of the previous incident, saidnofrh\ning of th\u201c circumstance.\nWednesday, howeer. it was discovered\ntdiat the man was dead. Investigation\ndisclosed the fact, as previously stat\n*'h V i i \u25a0\u25a0.lit'\"\ned, that tb\u00ab man had probably been\ndead since Sunday night.\nNothing was found on the body\nj that would lead to identification\nfurther than his name. Among his\neffects was found a certificate i of de-\nposit in the State Bank Trust com\npany for $100, issued at Fairviw on\nFebruary 14, lettetra addressed to\nhim at Rawhide and a deed to a sale\nof a quarter interest ia the New Yo\u00bbk\nmine at Rawhide to William Smith and\nEllis Golraith. ,A check was found\nshowing he had forwarded his baggage\nto Winnemucca.\nToday the autopsy on Adams showed\nthat ne had died from natural causes,\nprobably pneumonia. He had a large\nblister on his left side over the feeart\nand several other blisters on his. back.\nDr. Samuels states that this was proba-\nblv due to doctoring himself for a\ncold. I\nThe coroners jury brought in a ver-\ndiet of death from natural causes.\nTelegrams failed to locate anyone\nwho knew Adams, and his fnneral was\nheld from the undertaking parlors.\nMoney enough was found on hie body\nto defray all expenses connected .with\nthe funeral ,1\nWEATHER REPORT\nFollowing is the report of the local\noffice of the United States weather\nbureau of the department of agricul\nture for Winnenmeca for the twenty\nfour hours ending at 5 a. m., March\n5, 1908:\nMinimum temperature,\nMinimum temperature; 19. t\nBfc *an temperature. 312.\nNormal temperature, 37.\nPrevailing direction of the wind,\nsouthwest.\nForecast for VVinnemueea, Nevada,\nand vicinity for the twenty-four hours\nending at 5 p m., March 6, 1908, is\nsued from San Francisco.' Caliiornia:\nCloudy tonight; fair Friday.\nJ. C HAYDEN,\nOfficial in Charge.\n-o\u2014-- i\nBAWHIDE SANITARY\nCONDITIONS PERFECT\nDr. F. M. Lee, president of the state\nboard of health, returned to Carson\n\u00bbne day fast week, after Investigating\nthe health conditions at Rawhide, at\nthe reqtiest of Governor Sparks, and\nstates that the health and sanitary\nconditions in Rawhide are perfect. He\nsays that he does not believe there will\nbe much sickness at Rawhide this sum\nmer, and that if sewrers are placed\nin the camp it will be the most sani\ntary of all of the camps in Nevada.\nPLEASANT SURPRISE\n\nLast evening the home of Dr. Man\ngan was the scene of a pleasant sur\nprise party, given in honor of the\nbirthday of Mr. Lipinan. Cards was\nthe principal entertainment of the\nevepmg. After partaking of a dainty\nsupper all departed voting the party\na complete success.\n\u2014--o\nORA Y-MELVIN.\nA pretty wedding took place at the\nLafayette hotel yesterday, when W.\nH. Gray, a popular rancher 01 Spring\nvalley claimed Mrs. Me.vih of Union\nville for his bride. Miss Alice Wil\nsun acted as bridesmaid.\nAfter the eeremonv the tin-can bri\ngade put in an appearance and ser\nenaded the eouple.\nr -0\nN J- Moore, who has been sick with\na severe attack of pleurisy, js reportted\nbetter today.\nstriken individuals vrhieh produced so\nsuddenly the remarkable depression\nfrcrti which alf have suffered. They\npractically uniformly express confi\ndesire that the return of prosperity wii\nbeyjalmost ns sudden as was the com\ningj of adversity, and in their argil\nmolits as to the enforcement (if thi\nnise hour law they pointed out to the\nCommission that such a return of pros\npeijty might seriously embarras them\nin complying with the law, because it\nwtfQld render it difficult to Command\ntho services of competent operators in\nsufficient numbers t^> meet the nheds\nofrprbspefous eondifldns.\u2019\n\u25a0With fotir or five1 eTeoptfons, no 1m\nporrtant railroads in the country have\nindicated an intent?' n to reduce tin\nwages of their' employes.\ni II\n11 \u2018\"1 MUS 511],\nCLEVELAND, O, March-Lt-Over\n150 school children lost their lives Ur\nday in a fire whieh destroyed the\nthroe story brick school building on\nColhnner avenue, in tuollinwood, a ,y\\\nsuburb, just outside of the city limits..\nAt two o\u2019clock this evening 145 bodies\nhad been recovered* aud it is* believed\nthat there are several others in] the *n\nruins. The fire started in the basement\nof the building about ten o\u2019clock* just\nafter the school had convened. It was cm t(*\ncaused by an overheated furnace. The. f\nsmoke from the fire quickly filled the\nbuilding and alarmed the teachers and n\u00bb\nchildren. A panic ensued. Ho fire. ,i(*;\ndrill was used in rescuing the children i\nand they rushed pettoneli foe doors\nand windows. w\n'-i O' i n\nJames J. Hill left for San Jose,,,\nCalifornia last evening, where he wili\nmake his home in the future.\n\nHeadmaster Toombs of the Southern\nPacific spent Wednesday inspecting\nthe road at this place.\n1 11 i ic\nH. D Sellers the popular night ticket\nagent made a flying trip- t o Preble\"\"1\n\u25a0yesterday.\n'\u2018\",l \"\"l' i\nAlbert Hemusat the Clew creek\nsheep man is registered at the Win-\nnemueca.\nMr. Waterhouse of Herrin Hall and\nMarvin Safe company is in town to\nday. i. -,l\ni\nN. .1. Peirce is in down for a load of'\nsuppliee for his Pleasant Valley ranch.\nJ., Hi1 >11\nF. A. Hoi s confined-do kis room\nwith an atta< It of rhe Is grippe.\nM rs. F. L. ilutertre of (Jolconda ia\nvisiting Mrs. M. 8 Bonnifield. i\n1 it i ii\u00abnn\nState Auditor L. O. liendersou is.in\ntown on official bnsinesn. ,i\nw to.ft M .r-otVitnoe\nPan i>eBarron 'wf 'Jackson. miHUitsinNir i\n:s in town for a few days. v. mh,m. -uy.-.f.\n\nJ. S. Paw is hicke threatened with r r?\nui attack of pneumonia^ 'nnuuo\n--O-eV, f t,\nMrs. ft, N-. Robins-has returned'from\ni trip to Tomipuh. h* lie i -n\n1 I ft I mi I..\nA. F.' Johnson, consta We. af .Cttleoude i.,\nill town today. cm- n r 5-,\n.\u2022'\u2022'\u2022or t \u201ent nun \u2018i'll! ,